%I A397257 #26 Jul 16 2026 00:06:22
%S A397257 1,14,27,156,196
%N A397257 Fixed points of A093811, sum of the digital products of the divisors.
%C A397257 Next term, if it exists, is greater than 10^8.
%C A397257 The digital product (A007954) is smaller than n for all n > 9, often significantly smaller. Therefore, a larger fixed point can be expected to have divisors with relatively large digits on the average.
%C A397257 We conjecture that there are no further terms, but we don't have a formal proof yet.
%C A397257 We conjecture that for indices n ~ 10^k, record values of A093811 oscillate around 9^k. More precisely, A093811(n) < n for n > 10^3 (so this sequence is finite and complete), and A093811(10^k-2) = 9^k*4/3 sets a new record value for all k > 4, hence lim sup A093811(n)/n = 0.
%C A397257 There are no more solutions up to 10^9. - _David Radcliffe_, Jul 11 2026
%F A397257 { k | A093811(k) = k }.
%e A397257 For a(2) = 14, we have divisors(14) = {1, 2, 7, 14} and therefore A093811(14) = 1 + 2 + 7 + 1*4 = 14.
%e A397257 For a(3) = 27, we have divisors(27) = {1, 3, 9, 27} and therefore A093811(27) = 1 + 3 + 9 + 2*7 = 27.
%e A397257 For a(4) = 156, we have divisors(156) = {1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 12, 13, 26, 39, 52, 78, 156} and therefore A093811(156) = 16 + 2 + 3 + 12 + 27 + 10 + 56 + 30 = 156.
%e A397257 For a(5) = 196, we have divisors(196) = {1, 2, 4, 7, 14, 28, 49, 98, 196} and therefore A093811(196) = 14 + 1*4 + 2*8 + 4*9 + 9*8 + 1*9*6 = 196.
%p A397257 dp:= n-> mul(i,i=convert(n,base,10)):
%p A397257 f:= n-> add(dp(d), d=numtheory[divisors](n)):
%p A397257 select(n-> n=f(n), [$1..200])[];  # _Alois P. Heinz_, Jul 07 2026
%o A397257 (PARI) for(n=1, oo, A093811(n)==n && print1(n", "))
%o A397257 (PARI) is(n) = my(d = divisors(n), t = 0); forstep(i = #d, 1, -1, if(9^(#Str(d[i]))*i+t < n, return(0)); t+=vecprod(digits(d[i]))); t==n \\ _David A. Corneth_, Jul 08 2026
%Y A397257 Cf. A093811 (sum of digital product of divisors), A007954 (digital product).
%K A397257 nonn,hard,more,base,new
%O A397257 1,2
%A A397257 _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 07 2026
